1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bc4
{ [Source] and this is the Fischer variation this is where I want to get into and as you can see here as many of if you watch my videos the F7 square is a huge weakness for black especially early on when White's light Square Bishop can eye on it very easily and it's not protected by much besides the black king { [%ai The Fischer variation is an aggressive choice against the Sicilian, specifically targeting the f7 weakness.] }
6... e6
{ [Source] Black has the option to bring his Pawn to E6. It is a little defensive and passive but it effectively blocks the light-squared Bishop's path to F7. { [%ai A solid, prophylactic move that neutralizes the immediate pressure from the Fischer variation.] }
( 6... g6
{ [Source] but a lot of times a lot of players in this variation tend to think that need to bring their Pawn to G6 and I've seen it quite a few times about half and half and a lot of players think that they need to fianchetto their Bishop to G7 so that they can get more attacking on the center control and try to have a Counterattack on the dark squares eyeing from the G7 square with their dark Square Bishop but this is going to be a mistake { [%ai The defining inaccuracy that sets up the Magnus Smith Trap. By choosing g6 over the more solid e6, Black creates weaknesses on the f7 and d6 squares.] }
7. Nxc6
{ [Source] and from here white can capture this Rook or excuse me this Knight on C6 { [%ai A key preparatory move that removes the knight's defense of the d4 square and prepares the disruptive e5 advance.] }
7... bxc6
{ [Source] and black after he recaptured { [%ai Forced recapture. Although it strengthens Black's center, it opens lines for White's tactical exploitation.] }
8. e5
{ [Source] then white has the nice little move of playing Pawn to E5 and this is really what I want to look at right here { [%ai The point of the trap. This move challenges the f6 knight and exploits the alignment of the black queen and king.] }
8... dxe5
{ [Source] if black looks at it very quickly if he tries to retake with his Pawn { [%ai Falling headfirst into the trap. Black must instead move the knight to avoid immediate material loss.] }
( 8... Ng4
{ [Source] his Knight really has two moves where he can go he can always bring it back to G8 but you never want to develop a move develop a piece and then bring it right back you're going to lose a lot of momentum as far as Tempo gaining and White's going to have a huge developmental Advantage { [%ai White capitalizes on the displacement of the knight to gain tempo and control.] }
9. e6
